Pipe operator

This is an example of filtering observations from a dataframe without using the pipe operator

The pipe operator %>% basically chaining arguments together in a clear way.

Advantages:
- You’ll avoid nested function calls
- You’ll minimize the need for local variables and function definitions
- Easy to add steps anywhere in the sequence of operations.

As you’re getting more familiar with tidyverse you will understand the power of this concept.

TIDYING DATA

Main Libraries: tidyr, tibble

Tidy datasets are easy to manipulate, model, visualize and have a specific structure.

What is tidy data?

A set of data in a specific form:

  • Each variable is a column
  • Each observation is a row
  • Each value is a cell

This is an example of a messy dataset

datasets::WorldPhones

     N.Amer Europe Asia S.Amer Oceania Africa Mid.Amer

Here each column presents the number of phones in a specific area. Each row presents the number of phones per specific year. It is messy & very difficult to handle e.g. analyze, model…

This is an example of a tidy dataset

Gather

Essentially it takes a “wide” dataframe with a lot of columns and transforms it to “long”. It takes the following arguments:

  1. the key, where you create the group variable
  2. the value, which is the value variable (usually numeric)
  3. The columns you want to group

Use gather() to make a tidy dataframe

Spread

It converts a long dataframe into a wide dataframe. In practice it reverses the gather function, so it does the opposite of making tidy dataset. Sometimes it is used as an intermediate step in data transformation or when creating tables for reports or presentations

Separate

separate() takes string values in a single column and splits into multiple columns. The following arguments are used:

  1. The name of the column to separate
  2. The vector of new column names to separate into
  3. The character to separate the values by

SUMMARISING & GROUPING

Main Libraries: dplyr

Summarize single variable

We use summarise() to produce summaries of one or more variables. A new dataframe is created that consists of the specified summary.

Summarize multiple variables

Use it to create more transformations. You can do as many transformations as you want, just separate these by commas.

Use summarise_all() to summarise all variables. It can apply a single function to all variables of a dataframe. If the function doesn’t apply to a variable, it will produce a missing value.

iris %>% 
  summarise_all(mean)

argument is not numeric or logical: returning NA

Use summarise_at() to summarise specific variables by applying multiple functions.

iris %>% 
  summarise_at(vars(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width), funs(mean, median))

`funs()` is deprecated as of dplyr 0.8.0.
Please use a list of either functions or lambdas: 

  # Simple named list: 
  list(mean = mean, median = median)

  # Auto named with `tibble::lst()`: 
  tibble::lst(mean, median)

  # Using lambdas
  list(~ mean(., trim = .2), ~ median(., na.rm = TRUE))
This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
Call `lifecycle::last_warnings()` to see where this warning was generated.

Group by & summarise

Pass the variable name into group_by to create an individual group for each value in the column. It creates a dataframe for each group and then executes the chosen functions. At the end it reassembles the individual output. group_by() in conjunction with summarise() is one of the most important concepts in tidyverse.

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  summarise(Avg_Sepal.Length = mean(Sepal.Length))

`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

VISUALISE DATA

Library: ggplot2

We’ll explore the power of ggplot, which is probably the most powerful library for visualization in any programming language. There are significant packages in R and other languages (e.g. matplotlib, seaborn in Python) but nothing can compare to ggplot

There are 3 main elements in the ggplot syntax:

    1. ggplot() function called to initiate the plots

Initiate a plot by passing the dataframe as the first argument of the ggplot() or use the pipe operator %>%

ggplot(dataframe, ….) or dataframe %>% ggplot()

    1. aes() aesthetic layer used for representing the data

It defines the mappings to columns in the dataframe

ggplot(dataframe, aes(x = x_var)) or dataframe %>% ggplot(aes(x = x_var))

    1. You can add multiple layers to make a plot look the way desired Use the ‘+’ operator to add layers in the plot. The layers define what and how the plot gets rendered. The plot must have at least one layer in order to display

dataframe %>% ggplot(aes(x = x_var)) + geom_histogram()

Single Dimension plots

These are plots using a single variable.

E.g. geom_density(), geom_dotplot(), geom_freqpoly(), geom_histogram(), geom_bar()

You can use a lot of arguments in the geom_ layer functions. e.g.

It is easy to change the plot. e.g. below there is a density plot. We only need to change the last line function name

2D plots

Create plots with 2 variables in order to show their relationship. We add an additional variable to the aes() function. There are a lot of geom_ functions but the most common are geom_point(), geom_col(), depending on the variables data type.

Below there is a scatter plot

Below there is a bar plot. Here we perform some data transformations prior to the plotting.

iris %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% 
  summarise(Sepal.Width = mean(Sepal.Width)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Species, Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_col()

COMBINE TIDYVERSE PACKAGES

Here we combine tidying, wrangling, grouping, summarizing and plotting data.

WorldPhones %>% 
  
  # Make a tidy dataset
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column("year") %>% 
  gather(key = "Area", value = "Phones", N.Amer:Mid.Amer) %>% 
  filter(year > 1951) %>% 
  
  # Create the growth rate variable
  group_by(Area) %>% 
  mutate(previous_value = lag(Phones)) %>%
  mutate(growth_rate = (Phones-previous_value)/Phones) %>% 
  
  # Summarise the dataset
  group_by(Area) %>% 
  summarise(Avg_growth = mean(growth_rate, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  
  # Create the plot
  ggplot(aes(reorder(Area, -Avg_growth), Avg_growth)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    title = "Average growth rate of phones per area",
    subtitle = "Between 1956 & 1961",
    y = "Average growth rate (%)",
    x = "Area"
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent) +
  theme_bw()

`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
